{
  "doc_id": "39425",
  "text": "Increasing information is available concerning the pol mutations in clinical isolates that are markers of drug resistance (5-7) (Fig. 1) . Dual resistance to ganciclovir and cidofovir has been mapped to pol region IV (codons 379 to 421), codon 987 in region V, and a region between codons 501 and 545 [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The only baseline variation observed in these codon ranges is in the latter area (at codon 515). Foscarnet resistance has been mapped to codons 700, 715, 756, 781, 802, 809, and 821, involving regions II, III, and VI (codon range 696 to 845). Mutations in this region sometimes confer low-grade crossresistance to ganciclovir and other drugs [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . No baseline amino acid variation was observed in this region except at codon 697. An amino acid change at codon 676 was previously reported in association with a ganciclovir-cidofovir-resistant isolate [CITATION_10] . The same change was found in two sensitive isolates in this study and has been found by marker transfer to be unrelated to resistance to ganciclovir and cidofovir [CITATION_11] .",
